title: Valentine Gephart, September 1927
description: Transcribed from photograph:  "Valentine Gephart of Seattle, secretary of the National Aeronautic Association of the United States, will be in the cock pit as pilot of the City of Olympia, Capital of Washington, when she soars out from Roosevelt  field, Long Island, New York, as a Class B division contestant in the National Air Derby race from New York to Spokane, September 19-21. The flying secretary of the N.A.A. is a marine corps reserve pilot, having learned to fly during the war. His ship will be a Woodson M6 monoplane 2 place job, motored with a Detroit "air cat", radio cooled five cylinder engine. Gephart's entry was financed by a group of Olympia business men, who have promised to give him the plane if he wins the B class first price money of $5000."

title: Ben Tipp Jewelry Store at 3rd Ave. and Pine St., ca. 1935
description: A December 16, 1934 article notes Tipp's efforts to stay in business during the Great Depression, stating "During this period he has kept the personnel of his store up to twenty-six employees, and throughout the so-called depression times he has  maintained working conditions up to the same high standard. Satisfied employees and customers are another answer why Ben Tipp's is known as "The Store of Happiness.""

title: "Atlanta" in Ballard Locks, ca. 1929
description: The Atlanta was a steamboat built in 1908 and used for passenger service in Lake Washington and the Puget Sound. The boat was owned by Captain John L. Anderson of the Anderson Steamboat Company. In 1922, Anderson began using the boat for tours of Elliott Bay, the Ship Canal and Lake Washington through his company Anderson Water Tours. Anderson sold the boat in 1938.

title: Jim McDermott, April 3, 1980
description: Transcribed from short Oregonian article on back of photograph: "Vancouver, Wash. - Characterizing the current administration as one wrought with ""waste and squander,"" State Sen. James McDermott, D-Seattle, announced Wednesday that he will challenge Gov. Dixy Lee Ray - also a Democrat - for governor in 1980. McDermott, during a news conference in Vancouver, vowed to keep the quality of Washington life high and [caption cuts off]"

title: Brown Bear cartoon, August 15, 1955
description: Transcribed from back of photograph: "Cartoon of Brown Bear (holding Nasen bottle equipped with Reversing Thermometers and a bathy thermograph). Drawn by Art Welch, 25 August 1955." The Brown Bear was built in 1934 with funds from the Works Progress Administration. It was used by the U.S. Bureau of Biological Survey and the Alaska Game Commission for biological research excursion to Alaska. It was used during the U.S. Navy during World War II and acquired by the University of Washington Department of Oceanography in 1952.

title: Wrecked car being pulled from Lake Washington, May 12, 1955
description: Transcribed from photograph: "ARP - 051201 - 5/12/55 - SEATTLE: Body of Everett Chartrant sprawls on seat of his car as wreckers pull it from Lake Washington here (5/12). Chartrant traveling at ""east 90 miles per hour"" according to witnesses, struck bridge's draw span abutment and skidded and flew more than 120 feet to land on far side of well. (5/11). The car sank in 70 feet of water. Two US Navy Divers fastened cables to car so it could be hoisted from the water. UNITED PRESS TELEPHOTO."

title: Smith Cannery Machines Company, ca. 1915
description: The company was located at 2413 1st Ave. S. They were responsible for producing the "Iron Chink" which removed salmon heads, tails and fins before splitting the fish in half.

title: Aerial view of downtown Seattle from near 5th Ave. and Pike St., 1931
description: Photograph shows the view NW towards buildings such as the Seaboard Building, the Century Building the Bon Marche and the New Washington Hotel.

title: Steam shovel regrading 3rd Ave. near James St., 1907
description: Transcribed from photograph: "9865 - Cutting down a street with a steam-shovel, - Seattle, Washington. Copyright 1907 Underwood & Underwood." Hotel Mansfield, located at 3rd Ave. and James St. is visible in the upper right corner of the photograph.

title: Chardonnay Apartments at 203 Bellevue Ave. E., ca. 1930
description: Today, the building is called Chardonnay Apartments. When it was first built in 1906, it was known as The Bellevue.

title: Men outside Rivoli Gardens burlesque theatre on 1st Ave., March 1945
description: The 1943-44 City Directory lists the New Rivoli Gardens Theatre at 918 1st Ave. Eagle Jewelry and Sporting Goods Co. is listed at 920 1st Ave. (to the left) and Parks & Hart Billiards is listed at 916 1st Ave. (to the right). A stamp on the back of the photograph reads "Passed by U.S. 20634 Army Examiner."

title: King County Jail prisoners playing cards, December 3, 1932
description: Transcribed from caption on back of photograph: "207789. Quiet Game in Killers' Row. With an all-star team of killers taking part, a card game is in session in a cell at King County Jail, Seattle Wash. Of the six men, five are charged with murder, and one with shooting his father who is expected to die. Left to right: Richard Carter, charged with killing his foster-mother; Ted Bradley, sentenced to died January 29 for killing a grocer in hold-up; Edward Evans, charged with shooting father; Julian Marcelino, (standing) who stabbed six persons to death and wounded thirteen others; Alfred Labored, Filipino murder suspect; and throwing an ace card down is John Zerfass, sentenced to life imprisonment for shooting and killing a drugless healer. Credit Line (ACME) 12/2/32."

title: San Francisco Oyster House at 202 Yesler Way, ca. 1909
description: The San Francisco Oyster House began in the 1890s. It had to move from its Yesler location ca. 1912  to 216 James St. to make way for the construction of Smith Tower. Flags for the Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition hang in the front window.

title: 4th and Battery Building under construction, April 25, 1977
American soldiers and their Japanese wives arriving in Seattle, October 1951
description: Transcribed from photograph caption: "NY442-1/9-Tokyo, Japan: Of the 6,000 marriages between Japanese girls and American citizens in the occupation forces since 1945, many have been happy because soldiers like the "thoughtful and considerate ways" of the Japanese women. Above, 13 Japanese wives, almost all mothers, and their American soldier husbands are shown as they arrive in Seattle in October, 1951. (SUGGESTED FOR USE WITH UP STORY BY ERNEST HOBERECT FOR WEDNESDAY P.M.'s) UNITED PRESS-ACME. SEE NY441."

title: Cornish Follies, 1929
description: The Follies were a revue group from Cornish College offering skits, dances, songs and other entertainment.
subjects: Cornish College of Allied Arts (Seattle, Wash.)--Students

title: Man with Materials Reclamation Co. truck, ca. 1950
description: The 1948 City Directory lists the company at 911 Western Ave with Thomas O'Brube as the manager. The plant is listed at 1102 W. Hanford. The company is listed in the 1951 City Directory at 4201 W. Marginal Way. Thomas O'Burke and J.F. Thompson are listed as the proprietors.

title: Virginia McGrath in hospital after plane crash, November 18, 1955
description: Transcribed from photograph caption: "ARP-111806-11/18/55 - Seattle: Mrs. Virginia McGrath rests in hospital here (11/18) after escaping death in crash of DC-4 here (11/18). 73 persons were aboard the plan. 47 are reported to have survived. Mrs. McGrath, her husband, and her three children were aboard the plan. The children survived with minor injuries. The father is unaccounted for. UNITED PRESS TELEPHOTO." According to other news articles, the family was treated at Harborview Hospital.

title: Reindeer at Woodland Park, March 7, 1898
description: Transcribed from photograph: "9066 - Government Reindeer en route for Alaska, Woodland Park, Seattle, Wash., U.S.A. Copyright 1898 by B.L. Lingley. The reindeer, originally from Norway, were being shipped to Alaska to serve as pack animals for Alaskan gold seekers."

title: Men at Puget Sound Navy Yard with W.F. Young's Bolting-Up Jack, 1919
description: According to an article in International Marine Engineering, Volume 25 (available through Google Books) the jack was designed by W.F. Young, an employee at the Puget Sound Navy Yard to help construct ships more efficiently. The article includes diagrams of the tool and describes its uses.

title: Boy in front of bush, ca. 1919
Kalakala ferry, ca. 1940
description: The Kalakala operated between 1935 and 1967.

title: Rainier Tower construction and Olympic Hotel looking SE, February 18, 1975
description: The Olympic Hotel appears at the right. The IBM Building, Plymouth Congregational Church and the Park Place Office Building appear to the left.

title: "George Luckenbach" and "Sandra Foss" near Harbor Island, ca. 1955
description: The George Luckenbach (originally known as the S.S. Sea Star) was built in 1943 for the United States Maritime Commission. It was renamed during its service for the Luckenbach Steamship Company between 1948 and 1960. In 1960 the ship was sold to States Marine Lines and renamed Buckeye State. It was scrapped in 1973. The Sandra Foss was constructed in 1925 and remained in operation with the Foss Company until March 1, 1973.

title: Portraits of unknown young girl, ca. 1920
description: The Photo-Movie Shop was run by brothers Philip and Joseph Ernst. The brothers traveled to Alaska for the Klondike Gold Rush and lived in Nome for a time before moving to Seattle circa 1917 and opening the photography studio.

title: Woodland Park ride, April 1956
description: Photo is captioned "Woodlawn Park" but appears to be at Woodland Park.

title: Carrie and Petra on Vashon Island, ca. 1920
description: No further information is known about the two women depicted in the photograph.

title: King Radio host Frosty Fowler, January 12, 1968
description: Fowler worked for King for 10 years and hosted a regular morning show broadcast from the observation level of the Space Needle.

title: Neil Nesheim preparing the horns for a taxidermied goat, February 27, 1954
description: Transcribed from newspaper caption on back of photograph: "Headache?: Neil Nesheim drilled into a section of goat skull as he prepared to attach the horns in one stage of work in mounting the head of a mountain goat." The 1954 City Directory lists the company at 1712-1714 Broadway.

title: 3131 Elliott Building, ca. 1986
description: The sculpture ""Runners"" by David Govedare appears at the right.

title: Bertha Landes taking over the Mayor's office from Edwin J. Brown, June 14, 1926
description: Transcribed from caption on back of photograph: "Watch your credit SF112303 ""P&A Photos"" (Photo shows Mrs. Bertha K. Landes of Seattle, Wash. being greeted by retiring Mayor - Dr. Edwin J. Brown. Feminine hand takes reins at Seattle City Hall! Mrs. Bertha K. Landes was sworn as Mayor of Seattle, Washington, a few days ago, and at a short time after she outlined her views on law enforcement, the City Light Department, traffic problems and the budget. She appointed a new police chief - Searing, who started right in to clean house! This photo shows Mrs. Landes in Seattle (Wash.) City Hall, with Dr. Edwin J. Brown, the retiring Mayor, offering assurance of his interest and cooperation, at the time she took office. (EFM-B-6-14-26). Photo by Pacific & Atlantic Photos, Inc., 25 Park Place, New York City. Please credit "P&A Photo."

title: Herbert Niccolls, October 27, 1931
description: Transcribed from caption on back of photograph: "594947 - 8 - Watch your credit - International Newsreel Photos. Slug (Herbert Niccols). Youngest murderer on trial. Seattle, Wash. -- Here is Herbert Niccols, 12-years-old confessed slayer of Sheriff John Wormell, of Asotin County, Washington. Niccols, one of the youngest murder defendants ever to be tried in Washington, is shown in the Asotin County courthouse when his trial opened on Monday, October 26. The boy shot and killed the 72-year-old sheriff during a holdup of a shore. (N-10-27-31). Convicted sentenced to life." Niccolls' last name is misspelled in the article caption.

title: Kaleetan ferry, ca. 1972
description: The Kaleetan started Puget Sound ferry service on March 12, 1967. Transcribed from photograph: "Being replaced on the Seattle-Winslow run by the new MV Spokane is the older superferry MV Kalateen. Although she doesn't possess the cargo-carrying capacity of the new jumbo ferries, the Kalateen has many useful days ahead of her on the Edmonds-Kingston route. The 382-foot-long Kalateen can carry about 2,000 passengers, as can the Spokane, but holds only 160 cards while the newer vessel can transport 206 autos."

title: S.S. H.F. Alexander in dry dock at Seattle, March 11, 1923
description: Constructed in 1915, the H.F. Alexander was originally known as the "Great Northern." It was used for naval service between 1917 and 1922. Afterwards it was converted to a passenger liner and its name was changed. The ship provided war service again from July 1942 to March 1946 under the name George S. Simonds. It was scrapped in February 1948. The same photograph appeared in the Seattle Times on March 11, 1923 with the caption: "Liner H.F. Alexander in Drydock. After dominating the scenery in the yard of the Todd Dry Docks, Inc., for several weeks, the Admiral Line's huge coastwise speed queen, H.F. Alexander, was returned to the water last week. The vessel's great prow rose to a height that commanded a full view of Harbor Island and the waterways. The photograph gives an idea of the long slender graceful build of the famous ship, her lines enabling her to make the speed that ranks her as being the fastest merchant vessel under the American flag. She will leave the yard March 21 or 22 and will return to the Admiral Line's Seattle-California route Tuesday March 27. She will return to service all tuned up and reconditioned for a great year in the coastwise passenger service."
